The "European Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Pact for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a reference point for the whole world – a guide to transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda, for all to use, to achieve this.
Naturally, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is subject to this: a profusion of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy at first glance, a large number of involved and connected subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock the European bureaucracy.
But it's a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development objectives are clearly stated, the targets are defined based on objectives subject to a deadline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the displayed ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (a net zero greenhouse gas emission) by 2050, to set up a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed products from the industry, nor kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
The European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, the detractors will consider the announcements of public consultations as mere empty talk for dreamers.
But let's talk about pointless chatter with French President Emmanuel Macron, who has been facing protests turning into riots for over a year, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Both Macron and Piñera are convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both of them desperately search for a way to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American advocates of neoliberalism will once again mock, and claim that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But it's enough to look at the United States today.
If neoliberalism treats the planet like it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to put up with elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent railway connections, highways with roads in such poor condition that traffic cannot circulate, replaced by detours.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle now costs 8 billion dollars, if not more, and the financing is ensured by billionaires, large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and by determined interest groups set on lowering taxes and protecting the status quo at all costs.
The solutions brought by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be, not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational and not narrowly partisan acceptance).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it's an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy, exist in the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
We can decarbonize the energy system, switch to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows by combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructures.
But to do this, we have to overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that want to maintain the status quo.
The large oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but oil sector workers and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining through training, and other public aids.
The European plan reasonably claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
The Europe, like the other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, as for the new infrastructures, public markets, research and development, the renewal of industrial equipment, etc. The financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts will have to be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
The Europe represents about 9.1% of the world's carbon dioxide emissions, whereas the share of China is 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to implement its green pact in its entirety, it will be lost if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the green pact, which is rightful.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which have eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions are two times less than those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it doesn't make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the ill-fated cold war launched by America.
The hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist, in the face of the pressure exerted by the United States, decarbonization, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead proposes a positive and unambiguous partnership to this latter: working together to put in place sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
L’Europe has made a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
